    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/Collection.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Collection</code></a> is the root interface to the java Collections hierarchy.  <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/List.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>List</code></a> is  one sub interface which defines an ordered Collection, other sub interfaces are  <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/Queue.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Queue</code></a> which typically will store elements ready for processing (e.g. <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stack_%28data_structure%29\" rel=\"noreferrer\">stack</a>).</p>\n\n<p>The following diagram demonstrates the relationship between the different java collection types:</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/XhKOu.jpg\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/XhKOu.jpg\" alt=\"java collections\"></a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 59631,
      "reputation" : 14015,
      "user_id" : 178382,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cd62c2e5b65c928086f5c1b58d58f644?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Gian",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/178382/gian"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1279881847,
    "creation_date" : 1279881847,
    "answer_id" : 3317405,
    "question_id" : 3317381,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p><em>Collection</em> is a high-level interface describing Java objects that can contain collections of other objects.  It's not very specific about how they are accessed, whether multiple copies of the same object can exist in the same collection, or whether the order is important.  <em>List</em> is specifically an <em>ordered</em> collection of objects.  If you put objects into a List in a particular order, they will stay in that order.</p>\n\n<p>And deciding where to use these two interfaces is much less important than deciding what the concrete implementation you use is.  This will have implications for the time and space performance of your program.  For example, if you want a list, you could use an ArrayList or a LinkedList, each of which is going to have implications for the application.  For other collection types (e.g. Sets), similar considerations apply.</p>\n"
  }, {
